• us incedit ad ſuum altare, &c. After which his Miter, Ring, Paſtoral ſtaff are conſecrated, put on, and delivered to him by the Biſhop, with many Prayers, Solemnities, Croſſings, Bowings, Kneelings, Proſtrations, changes of habits, places and antique Geſtures, fitter for a Stage than a Church. When an Archbiſhop is conſecrated, he hath a Pall put on, and ſuperadded to all theſe forecited Veſtments, which muſt be uſed only upon certain ſpecial feaſts and occaſions, put on with the like ſuperſtitious Ceremonies and Formalities, recorded in the Roman Pontifical: the ſerious peruſal whereof, and of Durantus his Rationale Divinorum, l. 3, 4. is ſufficient to make all grave, judicious, ſober Chriſtians, to na • ſeate ſuch theatrical diſguiſes and Veſtments, on which grave old Biſhops over-much dote, as little Children uſe to do on their Babies, Toyes and Rattles.
